# Rule: Client Bundle & Lazy Loading Discipline

When generating client-side logic and interactive components, keep the initial payload lean to preserve Time to Interactive (TTI).

## Core Directives

- Use dynamic imports for non-critical, below-the-fold, or interaction-triggered UI.
- Do not include heavy dependencies in the initial client bundle when they are not needed for first paint/first interaction.
- Split features by intent: render-critical code loads first, deferred code loads on demand.

## Required Patterns

```tsx
const HeavyAnalyticsModal = dynamic(
  () => import("@/features/analytics/components/heavy-analytics-modal"),
  { ssr: false, loading: () => <ModalSkeleton /> }
);
```

## Anti-Patterns

- Importing heavy charting/modal/reporting libraries at the top level of route-critical components.
- Bundling secondary-route features into first-load bundles.

## Acceptance Criteria

- First interaction path does not load non-critical heavy modules.
- Deferred features are loaded only when needed by viewport or interaction.
